<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="29" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1437,255,1391]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,277,255,281]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
Males of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Simon" baseAuthorityYear="1884" box="[389,688,256,281]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Mecopisthes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crassirostris">
<emphasis box="[389,688,256,281]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Mecopisthes crassirostris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differ from other 
<taxonomicName box="[890,1120,256,282]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Mecopisthes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[890,1032,256,281]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Mecopisthes</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
by the combined characters of the carapace and palp: the prominent snout with distinct angularity below the eyes and the strongly developed posterior part of the suprategular apophysis. Females are recognized by the triangular median plate, square or rectangular in all other species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="29" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1437,255,1391]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,310,394,420]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Remark:</emphasis>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Simon" baseAuthorityYear="1884" box="[324,629,394,419]" class="Arachnida" family="Linyphiidae" genus="Mecopisthes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="crassirostris">
<emphasis box="[324,629,394,419]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Mecopisthes crassirostris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was described from the male from the French department Gard (
<bibRefCitation author="Simon, E." box="[159,317,432,458]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="180 - 885" refId="ref45283" refString="Simon, E. (1884) Les arachnides de France. Paris, 5, pp. 180 - 885." type="journal article" year="1884">Simon 1884</bibRefCitation>
) and later from the Pyrénées Orientales (
<bibRefCitation author="Simon, E." box="[847,1009,432,458]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="309 - 532" refId="ref45339" refString="Simon, E. (1926) Les arachnides de France. Synopsis generale et catalogue des especes francaises de l'ordre des Araneae; 2 e partie. Paris, 6, pp. 309 - 532." type="journal article" year="1926">Simon 1926</bibRefCitation>
). Subsequently, it was cited from Pampilhosa in 
<collectingCountry box="[324,423,469,495]" name="Portugal" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Portugal</collectingCountry>
by 
<bibRefCitation author="Machado, A. de" box="[467,664,469,495]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="1 - 69" refId="ref44685" refString="Machado, A. de B. (1949) Araignees nouvelles pour la faune portugaise (III). Memorias e Estudos do Museu Zoologico da Universidade de Coimbra, 191, 1 - 69." type="journal article" year="1949">Machado (1949)</bibRefCitation>
, and redescribed by 
<bibRefCitation author="Millidge, A. F." box="[903,1092,469,495]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="113 - 123" refId="ref44815" refString="Millidge, A. F. (1978) The genera Mecopisthes Simon and Hypsocephalus n. gen. and their phylogenetic relationships (Araneae: Linyphiidae). Bulletin of the British Arachnological Society, 4, 113 - 123." type="journal article" year="1978">Millidge (1978)</bibRefCitation>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Denis, J." box="[1103,1256,469,495]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="245 - 257" refId="ref43686" refString="Denis, J. (1949) Notes sur les erigonides. XVII. Additions et rectifications au tableau de determination des femelles. Descriptions d'especes nouvelles. Bulletin de la Societe d' Histoire Naturelle de Toulouse, 84, 245 - 257." type="journal article" year="1949">Denis (1949)</bibRefCitation>
was the first to illustrate the epigynum, without indicating where the specimen was collected. This female is clearly different from the female present in our material, collected together with males. At the moment is is not known to which species the female illustrated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Denis, J." box="[613,766,581,607]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29" pagination="245 - 257" refId="ref43686" refString="Denis, J. (1949) Notes sur les erigonides. XVII. Additions et rectifications au tableau de determination des femelles. Descriptions d'especes nouvelles. Bulletin de la Societe d' Histoire Naturelle de Toulouse, 84, 245 - 257." type="journal article" year="1949">Denis (1949)</bibRefCitation>
belongs.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="28" pageNumber="29" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1437,255,1391]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,353,618,644]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Description:</emphasis>
Male: Measurements: Total length 1.6–1.8; prosoma 0.70–0.79 long, 0.54–0.60 wide. Colour: Prosoma olive brown, protruding part yellow brown; legs olive brown to yellow brown; abdomen dark grey, with small, purplish brown dorsal scutum. Prosoma (
<figureCitation box="[902,1040,693,719]" captionStart="FIGURES 43–56" captionStartId="25.[151,269,1778,1802]" captionText="FIGURES 43–56. Figs 43–46. Erigonoplus nasutus (O.P.-Cambridge, 1875); 43. Male prosoma, lateral view; 44. Male palp, prolateral view; 45. Male palpal tibia, dorsal view; 46. Embolic division, anteroventral view. Figs 47–49. Maso douro Bosmans &amp; Cardoso new species; 47. Male palp, prolateral view, with denticulate hairs in detail; 48. Male palpal tibia, dorsal view; 49. Embolic division, anterior view. Figs 50-56. Mecopisthes crassirostris (Simon, 1884); 50. Male prosoma, lateral view; 51. Idem, dorsal view; 52. Male palp, prolateral view; 53. Male palpal tibia, dorsal view; 54. Embolic division, anteroventral view; 55. Epigynum, ventral view; 56. Vulva, ventral view (E = embolus; StA = suprategular apophysis; Tp = tailpiece)." pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Figs 50–51</figureCitation>
): Clypeus protruding in a distinct snout, forming a rectangular angle at eye level, behind the eyes and at fovea level with angularity. Eyes: a = 0.3, b = 1, c = 1, d = 1.2. Legs: Tibiae spineless; Tb Mt I = 0.63; Tb Mt IV absent. Palp (
<figureCitation box="[1214,1354,768,794]" captionStart="FIGURES 43–56" captionStartId="25.[151,269,1778,1802]" captionText="FIGURES 43–56. Figs 43–46. Erigonoplus nasutus (O.P.-Cambridge, 1875); 43. Male prosoma, lateral view; 44. Male palp, prolateral view; 45. Male palpal tibia, dorsal view; 46. Embolic division, anteroventral view. Figs 47–49. Maso douro Bosmans &amp; Cardoso new species; 47. Male palp, prolateral view, with denticulate hairs in detail; 48. Male palpal tibia, dorsal view; 49. Embolic division, anterior view. Figs 50-56. Mecopisthes crassirostris (Simon, 1884); 50. Male prosoma, lateral view; 51. Idem, dorsal view; 52. Male palp, prolateral view; 53. Male palpal tibia, dorsal view; 54. Embolic division, anteroventral view; 55. Epigynum, ventral view; 56. Vulva, ventral view (E = embolus; StA = suprategular apophysis; Tp = tailpiece)." pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Figs 52–54</figureCitation>
): Tibia with broad anterodorsal apophysis, terminally bluntly pointed and larger, blunt retrolateral apophysis; suprategular apophysis anteriorly composed of a slender black tooth accompanied by a membranous part, posteriorly of a grey, triangular sclerite, terminally denticulate; tailpiece straight, terminally pointed; embolus whiplike, describing one and a half circle.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="28.[151,1437,255,1391]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,299,954,980]" pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Female:</emphasis>
Measurements: Total length 1.9; prosoma 0.71 long, 0.56 wide. Colour: Prosoma olive brown, legs and abdomen as in male. Eye disposition: a = 0.5, b = 1, c = d = 1. Tibiae spineless, Tb as in male. Abdomen: Without scutum. Epigynum (
<figureCitation box="[630,720,1029,1055]" captionStart="FIGURES 43–56" captionStartId="25.[151,269,1778,1802]" captionText="FIGURES 43–56. Figs 43–46. Erigonoplus nasutus (O.P.-Cambridge, 1875); 43. Male prosoma, lateral view; 44. Male palp, prolateral view; 45. Male palpal tibia, dorsal view; 46. Embolic division, anteroventral view. Figs 47–49. Maso douro Bosmans &amp; Cardoso new species; 47. Male palp, prolateral view, with denticulate hairs in detail; 48. Male palpal tibia, dorsal view; 49. Embolic division, anterior view. Figs 50-56. Mecopisthes crassirostris (Simon, 1884); 50. Male prosoma, lateral view; 51. Idem, dorsal view; 52. Male palp, prolateral view; 53. Male palpal tibia, dorsal view; 54. Embolic division, anteroventral view; 55. Epigynum, ventral view; 56. Vulva, ventral view (E = embolus; StA = suprategular apophysis; Tp = tailpiece)." pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 55</figureCitation>
): With triangular median plate narrowing backwards. Vulva (
<figureCitation box="[159,248,1066,1092]" captionStart="FIGURES 43–56" captionStartId="25.[151,269,1778,1802]" captionText="FIGURES 43–56. Figs 43–46. Erigonoplus nasutus (O.P.-Cambridge, 1875); 43. Male prosoma, lateral view; 44. Male palp, prolateral view; 45. Male palpal tibia, dorsal view; 46. Embolic division, anteroventral view. Figs 47–49. Maso douro Bosmans &amp; Cardoso new species; 47. Male palp, prolateral view, with denticulate hairs in detail; 48. Male palpal tibia, dorsal view; 49. Embolic division, anterior view. Figs 50-56. Mecopisthes crassirostris (Simon, 1884); 50. Male prosoma, lateral view; 51. Idem, dorsal view; 52. Male palp, prolateral view; 53. Male palpal tibia, dorsal view; 54. Embolic division, anteroventral view; 55. Epigynum, ventral view; 56. Vulva, ventral view (E = embolus; StA = suprategular apophysis; Tp = tailpiece)." pageId="28" pageNumber="29">Fig. 56</figureCitation>
): Spermathecae suboval, separated by their maximal diameter.
</paragraph>
